<TABLE BORDER=0 cellpadding=4 border=0 cellspacing=0 WIDTH="95%"><TR ><TD COLSPAN=2><CENTER><FONT SIZE="2" COLOR="#F0DCA0" FACE="Verdana, Arial">T O P I C  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; R E V I E W</font></CENTER></TD></TR><TR background="http://www.larian.com/ubb/forumtextureL.jpg"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Patriarch</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Hehe agian some nagging with Questions.<P>First for the magic system. Will there be only battle spells or do the magic have a wider range. As far as you said there is a enchanting spell and learning teleport wouldn't be the worst idea or at least have the scroll  <IMG SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/smile.gif">. But I am thinking about other manipulative spells like levitate, flying, telekinesis. locking doors or breathing in water. <BR>If they are it would be great if they work everywhere and with every object. Its one of the things I don't like in the realms of arcania games, lots of spells you actually never need or didn't work properly. At one point you had to light a torch with fire kit also I had to mages capable of casting a burn spell  <IMG SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/frown.gif">.<BR>Concerning use of these spells, levitate for example is one of my favorites in p&p avoiding traps, I mean those nasty things going of when you step on them. <BR>Brings me to the next point traps. Will there be any, and when there are some how can you avoid them. With a Skill ? If yes how the skill works, do one have to turn it on like in BG, or does it work, maybe with another skill like 6th sense automaticly, let the character warn you. Something like : I have a bad feeling about this.     <BR>Will it be possible to run/jump into safety when you trigger a trap, or will one be hit in every case ?<BR>If you detect a trap will it be possible to trigger it from a safe place, with a pole/long weapon or something like that?<P>Coming to the last point. <BR>Will there be items like ropes, tools and ordinary stuff you can use ? For example tankards, buckets to catch some water to stop a fire. Just thinking about preparing a hideout in a dungeon, put out some torches and attack the monsters from the shadows or just remove a torch from the wall to have light in a dark area. Hmm doing this could be tricky to programm light and shadows, so I think one can't do this, but it still would be great.<BR>Just in the case you have planned or already implemented a realistic journey mode, with all the equipment needed to do so. Tents, spare weapons, food, water etc. please add a horse or something like that to carry the whole stuff. <P><P>------------------<BR>never trust a smiling Dragon<P>Patriarch<P><BR></FONT></TD></TR><TR background="http://www.larian.com/ubb/forumtexture.jpg"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Anastasia</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Nah, no horse.<BR>Need something not so ordinary. Give us a quest and we will be rewarded our own little dinosaur upon completion  <IMG SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/smile.gif"><P>And another comment: there should be a permanent skill for detection of traps like 6th sense. I didn´t like that in BG (having to turn it off or on). Either a character is good at detecting traps or he sucks. If he´s a pro he doesn´t need to switch his mind to detection mode, does he ? </FONT></TD></TR><TR background="http://www.larian.com/ubb/forumtextureL.jpg"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">rat</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Well, there are basically 3 types of spells, the offensive kind (freeze an enemy, cast a fireball), defensive (teleport yourself away), and utility spells.  I guess the first two categories are only useful in battles, but the utility category has stuff ilke casting a teleportal, peeking through the shroud (fog of war), telekinesis etc.  There's also some stuff which we category as "defensive" but which may be useful for other things too if you're smart, like summoning a duplicate of yourself.</FONT></TD></TR><TR background="http://www.larian.com/ubb/forumtexture.jpg"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Risini Visinimi</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Hi all!<P>There is one thing I hated in all common CRPGs:<P>There is a woden door. Why aren't I able to burn it down? If I would use a sword or ax, I could cruch it. The sword would be dameged.<P>An other quest could even be, that you are on a way donwn in an dugeon. But then a iron or stone door in front of you. Cou can't open it whith might, but then you rember the huge barrel 200 m ago. You went back tip it and let it role against the door. (you rember it went down?)<BR>That would smach the door out of his angels.<P><P>------------------<BR>Will you never forget how to laught!<P>Risini Visinimi</FONT></TD></TR><TR background="http://www.larian.com/ubb/forumtextureL.jpg"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">rat</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Yeah, that's a problem <I>all</I> games have.  There are only two possibilities.. The first is to script this kind of tricks one by one.  But if this is not done right, the player doesn't have the idea that he was innovative, rather he thinks he just found the clue to solve the puzzle.  Only if the number of options is really huge do you get the feeling that you really came up with a way around an obstacle yourself, rather than merely discovering what you were supposed to do.<BR>But, the only way to get a really large amount of options is to just create a realistic world, and let it run on full autopilot.  This hasn't really been done yet, and probably won't be done in the near future, for technical reasons, but also : how do you script an interesting story or quest in such a world ?  If the world is totally open then how can you plot out a cool sequence of events ?  This is like the problem of a fully automatic world where the story unfolds outside the player's view and the game plays itself (they had this in Bladerunner for instance and had to restrict what the NPCs did), but even worse..<P>I don't know.. any thoughts ?</FONT></TD></TR><TR background="http://www.larian.com/ubb/forumtexture.jpg"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Marian</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Ah, that reminds me, Rat. Could you bring the Bladerunner into the office if you pass by next time please? </FONT></TD></TR><TR background="http://www.larian.com/ubb/forumtextureL.jpg"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Anastasia</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Well, Risini, I can tell you why you´re not able to burn a door down. Have you ever tried to ignite a door of solid wood with matches ? I haven´t either but I guess it takes many many matches to get it to burn. Some gas or other accelerator may help but then you got the problem of the whole damn place burning like hell. Not exactly a smart idea to burn doors down if you don´t know what´s behind that door, right ?<BR>But crushing would be an a-ok way of opening doors if they aren´t too solid. Agree on that.</FONT></TD></TR><TR background="http://www.larian.com/ubb/forumtexture.jpg"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Dante</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Well, it WOULD be nice that you can solve things otherwise than via hacking, but Ifollow Rat in his fear to implement a whole world model.<P>Magic usually does the trick:<BR>- *knock* spell to destroy open doors<BR>- levitation spells to walk over ramps (instead of having to use ropes)<BR>- light spells to create light<P>The only problem remains: what with fighter-only characters?<BR></FONT></TD></TR><TR background="http://www.larian.com/ubb/forumtextureL.jpg"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Goemoe</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Don't understand Dante.<P>What is with them? They don't have magic, so they can't use it, but this doesn't mean they are as dump as an anvil, they need not hack everything. They can very well buy or find a key for a locked door or can talk some weird minds out of their problems. And if they run into an unseen trap so be it.<P>Each class has certain advantages and disadvantages making this games interesting for each type of gamer. Would all classes could do the same, there wouldn't be any need for seperate professions, right?<P>Goemoe</FONT></TD></TR><TR background="http://www.larian.com/ubb/forumtexture.jpg"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Alrik Fassbauer</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">A different method would be to "hack" the door, well I don't know at the moment how to translate it into english, but in german I thought, dass es möglich sein könnte, das Schloss der Türe zu knacken...<BR><P>------------------<BR>MFG (Mehr Fürs Geld), Alrik. <BR></FONT></TD></TR><TR background="http://www.larian.com/ubb/forumtextureL.jpg"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Arhu</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial"><I>Crack</I>'s the word you've been struggling for, Alrik. Crack the lock open. (Nice dictionary. *pat the book*.  <IMG SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/smile.gif">) Or you could pick it with a skeleton key.<P>... And an experienced rogue could use arrowheads to open it. (just kidding)<P><I>Meow...</I><BR>Arhu<P>Oh btw, Lar, limited arrows are yet another way of 'weakening' the bow.<P>PS: Will the arrows be as slow as the ones in Baldurs Gate?</FONT></TD></TR><TR background="http://www.larian.com/ubb/forumtexture.jpg"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Dante</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Goemoe,<P>OK. But you don't expect to find keys of locked doors just hanging around. I mean, you can find the lock of my garden's shack somewhere in my house, but not e.g. the deposit vault's key somewhere hidden at some counter of the bank.<P>But you're right. Every character class has its own advantages. Care should only be taken such that not one class is blocked somewhere in the story.<P>Talking and persuasion would be a nice feat of the fighter anyhow: a mage could use his charisma to convince the gatekeeper to hand over the key to the gate, but a fighter would certainly need not such long talks: he just says "Gimme or I'll kick your butt".<P>PS: (especially for Paladin) not all figthers are uncharismatic or dumb (as the one above) but I put it like that just to illustrate my thoughts</FONT></TD></TR><TR background="http://www.larian.com/ubb/forumtextureL.jpg"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Alrik Fassbauer</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">so I try to persuade the door to let itself open...<BR> <IMG SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/wink.gif"><BR><P>------------------<BR>MFG (Mehr Fürs Geld), Alrik. <BR></FONT></TD></TR><TR background="http://www.larian.com/ubb/forumtexture.jpg"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Anastasia</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Well, Alrik. This actually works, doesn´t it ?<BR>Or have you never watched "Sindbad and the 40 thieves" as a child ?<BR>"Open Sesame" is the code word  <IMG SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/wink.gif"><BR></FONT></TD></TR><TR background="http://www.larian.com/ubb/forumtextureL.jpg"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Alrik Fassbauer</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">THAT would be a niche "Easter Egg" in a game !  <IMG SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/wink.gif"><BR><P>------------------<BR>MFG (Mehr Fürs Geld), Alrik. <BR></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
